        <div type="recipe">
        <p> Take two Ounces of Ising-glass, steep it all Night in Rose-Water; then take it out of the Water and put to it a <objectName ref="quart">Quart</objectName> of Milk, and about six Laurel Leaves, breaking the Leaves into two or three Pieces; boil this ’ till all the Ising-glass is dissolv ’ d, and the Milk diminish ’ d to less than a Pint; then put to it a <objectName ref="quart">Quart</objectName> of Cream, letting it boil about half an Hour; then strain it thro ’ a thin Strainer, leaving as little of the Ising-glass in the Strainer as you can; sweeten it, and, if you like it, put in a little Orange-Flower-Water; put it in a broad Earthen Pan, or China Dish; the next Day, when you use it, cut it with a Jagging-Iron in long Slips, and lay it in Knots on the Dish or Plate you serve it up in. </p>
            </div>
